<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-customization" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Customization</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      As mentioned at the beginning of this book, readers are expected to have
      some basic knowledge of R Markdown. This chapter focuses on how
      <c>bookdown</c> output can be customized, either with simple YAML
      metadata options or by replacing larger pieces of the Pandoc template.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="yaml-options">
    <title>YAML options</title>

    <p>
      For most output formats, the syntax-highlighting style can be customized
      with the <c>highlight</c> option. The Rmd source shows choosing the
      <c>tango</c> style for the <c>gitbook</c> format.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
output:
  bookdown::gitbook:
    highlight: tango
---</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      For HTML output, the most common customization point is the <c>css</c>
      option. A more general option is <c>includes</c>, which works for both
      HTML and LaTeX and provides the <c>in_header</c>, <c>before_body</c>, and
      <c>after_body</c> sub-options.
    </p>

    <p>The Rmd chapter illustrates the basic structure of an HTML document:</p>

    <program language="html">
      <input>&lt;html&gt;

  &lt;head&gt;
  &lt;!-- head content here, e.g. CSS and JS --&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;

  &lt;body&gt;
  &lt;!-- body content here --&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;

&lt;/html&gt;</input>
    </program>

    <p>It also shows the corresponding high-level LaTeX document structure:</p>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\documentclass{book}

% LaTeX preamble
% insert in_header here

\begin{document}
% insert before_body here

% body content here

% insert after_body here
\end{document}</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      One HTML example inserts a MathJax configuration file into the page head
      so displayed equation numbers appear on the left instead of the right.
    </p>

    <program language="html">
      <input>&lt;script type="text/x-mathjax-config"&gt;
MathJax.Hub.Config({
  TeX: { TagSide: "left" }
});
&lt;/script&gt;</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
output:
  bookdown::gitbook:
    includes:
      in_header: mathjax-number.html
---</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter also notes that comment systems such as Disqus or Hypothesis
      (<url href="https://disqus.com" visual="disqus.com"/>,
      <url href="https://hypothes.is" visual="hypothes.is"/>) can be embedded
      in the same way through <c>includes</c> (see
      <xref ref="collaboration"/>).
    </p>

    <p>
      For LaTeX output, the same mechanism can be used to add packages or
      preamble fixes. The Rmd source gives this example preamble file.
    </p>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\usepackage{booktabs}
\usepackage{longtable}

\ifxetex
  \usepackage{letltxmacro}
  \setlength{\XeTeXLinkMargin}{1pt}
  \LetLtxMacro\SavedIncludeGraphics\includegraphics
  \def\includegraphics#1#{% #1 catches optional stuff (star/opt. arg.)
    \IncludeGraphicsAux{#1}%
  }%
  \newcommand*{\IncludeGraphicsAux}[2]{%
    \XeTeXLinkBox{%
      \SavedIncludeGraphics#1{#2}%
    }%
  }%
\fi</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
output:
  bookdown::pdf_book:
    includes:
      in_header: preamble.tex
---</input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="theming">
    <title>Theming</title>

    <p>
      Sometimes the goal is to change the overall look and feel rather than add
      a single snippet. The chapter explains that formats such as
      <c>gitbook</c>, <c>tufte_html_book</c>, and <c>tufte_book2</c> already
      have stronger built-in themes, while <c>html_book()</c> and
      <c>pdf_book()</c> are more open to customization.
    </p>

    <p>
      For <c>html_book()</c>, the default style is Bootstrap as described in
      <xref ref="bootstrap-style"/>, and one of the built-in Bootstrap themes
      can be selected with the <c>theme</c> option.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
output:
  bookdown::html_book:
    theme: united
---</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      If none of the built-in Bootstrap styles are suitable, the chapter
      recommends setting <c>theme</c> to <c>null</c> and using custom CSS or
      HTML includes instead.
    </p>

    <p>
      For <c>pdf_book()</c>, one common customization is changing the document
      class. The Rmd source gives the KOMA-Script <c>scrbook</c> class as an
      example.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
documentclass: scrbook
output:
  bookdown::pdf_book:
    template: null
---</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      When changing document classes, an additional Pandoc argument may be
      needed so top-level headings are treated as chapters.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>documentclass: krantz
output:
  bookdown::pdf_book:
    pandoc_args: --top-level-division=chapter</input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="templates">
    <title>Templates</title>

    <p>
      Pandoc uses templates when converting Markdown to other output formats.
      These templates are plain-text files containing variables such as
      <c>$title$</c> and <c>$body$</c> that Pandoc later substitutes.
    </p>

    <program language="html">
      <input>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;$title$&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;

  &lt;body&gt;
  $body$
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</input>
    </program>

    <p>The chapter then gives this simple Markdown input document:</p>

    <program language="markdown">
      <input>---
title: A Nice Book
---

# Introduction

This is a **nice** book!</input>
    </program>

    <p>Applying the template yields HTML like the following:</p>

    <program language="html">
      <input>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;A Nice Book&lt;/title&gt;
  &lt;/head&gt;

  &lt;body&gt;

  &lt;h1&gt;Introduction&lt;/h1&gt;

  &lt;p&gt;This is a &lt;strong&gt;nice&lt;/strong&gt; book!&lt;/p&gt;

  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter explains that HTML, LaTeX, and EPUB templates are more
      complex in practice, but they follow the same idea. It also points readers
      to Pandoc's documentation and template repository for the full list of
      available variables.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="configuration">
    <title>Configuration</title>

    <p>
      In addition to chapter files and output formats, a book can be configured
      through <c>_bookdown.yml</c>. The Rmd chapter lists optional settings such
      as the merged-book filename, pre/post chapter scripts, edit/history/view
      links, output directory, and clean-up targets.
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><c>book_filename</c></p></li>
      <li><p><c>delete_merged_file</c></p></li>
      <li><p><c>before_chapter_script</c></p></li>
      <li><p><c>after_chapter_script</c></p></li>
      <li><p><c>edit</c>, <c>history</c>, and <c>view</c></p></li>
      <li><p><c>rmd_subdir</c> and <c>include_md</c></p></li>
      <li><p><c>output_dir</c></p></li>
      <li><p><c>clean</c></p></li>
    </ul>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>book_filename: "my-book.Rmd"
delete_merged_file: true
before_chapter_script: ["script1.R", "script2.R"]
after_chapter_script: "script3.R"
view: https://github.com/rstudio/bookdown-demo/blob/master/%s
edit: https://github.com/rstudio/bookdown-demo/edit/master/%s
output_dir: "book-output"
clean: ["my-book.bbl", "R-packages.bib"]</input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="internationalization">
    <title>Internationalization</title>

    <p>
      If the language of a book is not English, certain automatically generated
      labels and interface strings may need translation. For non-LaTeX output,
      these values can be configured in the <c>language</c> field of
      <c>_bookdown.yml</c>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Rmd chapter shows an R snippet that prints the default language
      settings from internal <c>bookdown</c> objects.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>```{r echo=FALSE, comment='', results='asis'}
cat('```yaml\n')
cat(yaml::as.yaml(list(language = list(
    label = c(bookdown:::label_names, bookdown:::label_names_math2),
    ui = bookdown:::ui_names
  ))
))
cat('```')
```</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      A simple label customization example changes the figure prefix to
      uppercase.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>language:
  label:
    fig: "FIGURE "</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter also gives an example of using expressions for both labels and
      UI terms, here in Hungarian.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>language:
  label:
    fig: !expr function(i) paste(i, 'ábra')
  ui:
    chapter_name: !expr function(i) paste0(i, '. fejezet')</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Finally, the chapter notes an important caveat for languages using pure
      CJK headings: Pandoc may not generate identifiers automatically, so manual
      identifiers may need to be appended to section headings for
      cross-references.
    </p>
  </section>
</chapter>
